    <h2>What I Built</h2>
    <p>The goal of this project was to visualize real security data using Grafana — so rather than working with sample data, a fully functional SOC was built from scratch.</p>
    <p>The lab was set up with three machines: Ubuntu1 and Ubuntu2 as the target, Kali Linux as the attacker. Attacks were launched against the target and the system's detection and response was observed in real time.</p>

    <h2>The Stack</h2>
    <p><strong>Tools used:</strong></p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Grafana</strong> — Real-time dashboards with alert rules</li>
        <li><strong>Prometheus</strong> — Pulling system metrics (CPU, memory, network, disk, load)</li>
        <li><strong>Loki</strong> — Storing and searching Zeek IDS logs</li>
        <li><strong>Zeek IDS</strong> — Capturing network events and threats in real time</li>
        <li><strong>Node Exporter</strong> — System metrics from the target machine</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Everything feeds into each other: Zeek captures network events → Loki stores them → Prometheus collects system metrics → Grafana displays it all in real time → alerts trigger on detected attacks.</p>

    <h2>What It Does</h2>
    <p><strong>The dashboard provides:</strong></p>
    <ul>
        <li>System health monitoring (CPU, memory, network throughput, disk I/O, load average)</li>
        <li>Real-time attack detection (port scans, DoS floods, ICMP floods as they happen)</li>
        <li>Attack timeline showing when attacks started and how they progressed</li>
        <li>Geographic map showing where attacks originate</li>
        <li>Table of top attack sources with IP tracking</li>
        <li>Live searchable logs for incident investigation</li>
    </ul>
    <p>When an attack is detected, the system sends an email alert with the full details — attack type, origin, event count, and system impact — providing everything needed to respond effectively.</p>

    <h2>The Key Part: Real Data</h2>
    <div class="section-intro">
        <p>Every number on the dashboard is real. No dummy metrics, no test data, no hardcoded values.</p>
    </div>
    <p>Every stat comes from an actual query on an actual machine under attack. Port scans are detected because Zeek saw them. DoS floods appear because Prometheus captured the packet spike. CPU spikes show because the system was genuinely under load.</p>
    <p>This approach took considerably longer than working with placeholder data, but it was essential — a well-designed dashboard built on fake data teaches nothing about real threat detection.</p>

    <h2>How It Was Tested</h2>
    <p>Real attacks were launched against the lab environment:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>nmap port scans → detected by the system, shown on the dashboard, email alert fired</li>
        <li>hping3 DoS floods → CPU spiked, network throughput exploded, attack logged</li>
        <li>ICMP floods → detected in real time and tracked across the timeline</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Every simulated attack was successfully detected and logged by the monitoring stack.</p>

    <h2>What This Project Demonstrated</h2>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Security isn't about one tool.</strong> It's about how tools work together. Zeek finds threats, Prometheus measures impact, Loki stores details, Grafana correlates them, and alerts drive response.</li>
        <li><strong>Real data is non-negotiable.</strong> A system has to actually see real threats to be meaningful — fake metrics don't prepare anyone for real incidents.</li>
        <li><strong>SOCs exist to enable response, not to look impressive.</strong> Every panel on the dashboard answers one question: "What do I need to know right now to respond to this attack?" If it doesn't answer that, it's just decoration.</li>
        <li><strong>Hands-on builds understanding.</strong> Reading about SOCs and actually building one — then attacking it — are two completely different levels of learning.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Conclusion</h2>
    <p>This project resulted in a fully functional SOC dashboard that detects attacks, visualizes them in real time, and triggers automated alerts. Every component was tested against live simulated attacks and performed as expected. It demonstrated that understanding cybersecurity defense requires understanding the entire pipeline — from detection to alerting to response — and that pipeline only becomes clear when you build it yourself.Special thanks to Professor Walter Delatorre for structuring this course in a way that encouraged real exploration over checkbox assignments — the open-ended approach made this level of depth possible.</em></p>

